<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-744-734  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 744 734.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  August 13 1990 v7 n32 p27(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>English-language capabilities set Occam's data-analysis toolapart. (Occam Research Inc.'s Muse data retrieval software)(Software) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ferranti, Marc.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Occam Research Inc's data analysis software, Muse, enables usersto enter natural language (English) queries to manipulate andanalyze data on an Apple Macintosh SE with at least 2Mbytes ofRAM.andP;  Muse works with relational data bases to help users see therelationships among different data sets and types of data.andP;  Betatesters indicate that the valuable feature of Muse and what givesit a significant advantage over other data analysis tools is itsnatural-language interface.andP;  Data may be entered or imported in avariety of file formats; they are linked by Muse's datadictionaries.andP;  Muse provides the user with the means to view datafrom a number of perspectives.andP;  Occam is demonstrating the packageat the Aug 1990 MacWorld Exposition in Boston and plans to beginshipping of the first version in Oct. Versions supporting UNIX andMS-Windows are in the works.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Occam Research Corp. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Muse (Search software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionData AnalysisSoftware PackagesNatural Language Interfaces.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Marc FerrantiandM;There are a handful of multidimensional-data analysis tools on the market,but Occam Research Inc.'s edge is the natural-language capabilities in itsMuse, a Macintosh data retrieval and manipulation package unveiled atMacWorld last week.andM;Muse allows users to write English-language queries to call up and view, intabular or graph form, relationships among different sets of data from arelational database, according to Neal Hill, president of Occam in Danvers,Mass.andM;&quot;The database, spreadsheet and graphics all relate through the languagemodule, giving a fluidity and control over data that other programs don'thave,&quot; he said.andM;&quot;What makes this product unique is its natural-language capability,&quot; saidFrank Morelli, a Muse beta tester and associate director of marketing anddecision-management systems at Colgate-Palmolive Co., a personal-careproducts firm in New York.andM;&quot;This also makes the program acceptable to users in marketing and sales --who may not use their computers that much -- because it allows them to useterms they're familiar with.andP;  It doesn't limit the way you can askquestions,&quot; he added.andM;Data is keyed in, or imported from other applications through a variety ofindustry-standard file formats, and stored in a relational database.andP;  Asusers bring data into the program, they define it in English.andP;  These terms,along with a core vocabulary, are stored in data dictionaries and can laterbe used to refer to and query for data, officials said.andM;Muse shows data in on-screen boxes called WorkBooks, which use therow-and-column spreadsheet format to display numbers.andP;  Users can use eachWorkBook to manipulate eight dimensions of data.andP;  They can display on-screenfour dimensions of data (rows and columns, each broken down into twocategories), they said.andM;Although programs such as Sinper Corp.'s TM/1 and ManageWare Inc.'s Compete!andO;permit users to view different relationships among multiple sets of data,&quot;the key difference is that natural-language processing is at the core ofMuse,&quot; Hill said.andM;Analysts who have evaluated the product emphasized the difference betweenMuse and two-dimensional spreadsheets.andM;&quot;With traditional spreadsheets, the way data goes in is the way you get itback,&quot; said Gladys Francis, an analyst at market-research firm Dataquest Inc.andO;in San Jose, Calif.andP;  &quot;Muse makes it easy to get different views on data.&quot;andM;Muse's graph types include a variety of 2-D and 3-D charts.andP;  It also supportsclipboards and scrapbooks for moving screen contents into other packages.andM;The program requires an Apple Macintosh SE and 2M bytes of RAM, and will beavailable directly from the company to consultants and information managersbeginning in October.andP;  The company is planning Windows and Unix ports of theproduct.andM;Occam can be reached at (617) 923-3545.andO;</TEXT></DOC>